In article y25k@andrew.cmu.edu, Ian S Nelson <in22+@andrew.cmu.edu> () writes:
>
>I have a question regarding this Clipper chip deal.  
>
>As I understand it, DES has a 56bit key and Clipper is supposed to have
>an 80bit key composed of two 40bit keys put together.  Would I be wrong
>in assuming that if you can derive one half of the Clipper key, you can
>find the other half?  (you can with RSA right?)  

     Wrong, the key is escrowed as two 80-bit strings that are
     XOR'd together to give you the key.  Having one of them
     is about as much use as an electric drill for lighting the house.
     
     Alec Chambers

>My conventional wisdom tells me that if that's the case, Clipper would
>then be weaker than DES based upon key size.  (2**56 DES keys and only
>2**40 keys to find full Clipper key)  
>
>Is this true?  If it is, has it been argued to the government that this
>is unacceptable?  

     It's not true.
>
>I can understand the key escrows and what they are supposed to do, but
>as it is, DES isn't all that hard to crack on a relative scale and
>Clipper would then be even easier.  The escrows would be worthless if
>anybody with a little money and some time can crack it.
>
>Please tell me I am wrong in this line of thinking,

     Basically, you went off half-cocked.
     
     Alec Chambers



